                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d168">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/4723: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-06-26T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 26, 1936—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 26—2:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>255. The Cuban Minister has just called on me and shown me a telegram from his
                    Government stating that the Argentine Minister at Habana had solicited Cuban
                    support in the Assembly and instructing him to accord such support. The telegram
                    added that Cuba favored the policy of nonrecognition and the discarding of
                    sanctions.</p>
                <p>He is telegraphing his Government urging that they instruct him rather to adopt
                    the Peruvian policy described in my telegram 250, June 24 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >25</hi>], 8 p.m.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
